{"type":"system","subtype":"task_started","task_id":"ac1b72ec07752b378","tool_use_id":"toolu_01JoefhpidbdwCMGm8obaPNk","description":"Security review of SYN-205 email update fix","subagent_type":"security-reviewer","task_type":"local_agent","prompt":"Audit the uncommitted working-tree changes in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/repos/fl-admin-portal on branch fix/syn-205-0909 (base: dev) for security issues.\n\nContext: SYN-205 fixes a bug in the member-profile update flow (web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/UpdateMember.tsx). Apollo Client uses `errorPolicy: 'all'`, so a GraphQL error from the UpdateMemberDetails mutation (e.g. a server-side email/whatsapp collision check) was landing in the mutation result's `errors` array instead of rejecting the promise — the old code's try/catch never fired, so the UI treated a REJECTED write as a success: it ran follow-up bacenta/basonta mutations, reset the form, and navigated away, while the actual profile data was never saved.\n\nThe fix: onSubmit now explicitly checks `updateResult.errors`. If the error carries `extensions.collision` (a specific server-side collision payload: field, status, memberId, firstName, lastName, bacentaName), it's routed to the existing MemberCollisionDialog. Any other GraphQL error calls the existing `displayError` util and returns before the follow-up mutations/navigation run.\n\nRun `git diff dev...fix/syn-205-0909 -- web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/UpdateMember.tsx web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/UpdateMember.test.tsx` to see the exact diff.\n\nFocus areas: does surfacing `updateResult.errors[0]` via `displayError` risk leaking any sensitive server error detail to the client UI (e.g. stack traces, internal identifiers) that it shouldn't? Does the collision payload (memberId, firstName, lastName, bacentaName of the OTHER colliding member) get exposed to a user who may not have permission to see that other member's info — is this pre-existing behavior (already used by the same MemberCollisionDialog elsewhere) or newly introduced by this change? Is there any risk of the fix bypassing or weakening the isAuth/permission checks elsewhere in this file? Report Critical/High/Medium/Low.","uuid":"fa24c3ba-7d44-45c4-936d-c4bbe37fc72d","session_id":"1f8dd599-a4b3-4691-9eeb-51a7fceb4862"}
