{"type":"system","subtype":"task_notification","task_id":"ac1b72ec07752b378","tool_use_id":"toolu_01JoefhpidbdwCMGm8obaPNk","status":"completed","output_file":"/tmp/claude-1000/-home-ubuntu--openclaw-workspace-repos-fl-admin-portal/1f8dd599-a4b3-4691-9eeb-51a7fceb4862/tasks/ac1b72ec07752b378.output","summary":"I reviewed the actual working-tree diff (the `dev...fix/syn-205-0909` range is empty since these are uncommitted changes; the real diff is `git diff dev -- web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/UpdateMember.tsx` plus the new `UpdateMember.test.tsx`), and traced every dependency it touches: `web-react-ts/src/utils/errorHandler.ts`, `web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/MemberCollisionDialog.tsx`, `api/src/resolvers/utils/utils.ts` (`memberContactCollisionError`), and `api/src/resolvers/directory/directory-resolvers.ts` (`UpdateMemberDetails`, `UpdateMemberBacenta`, `CreateMember`, `ReactivateMemberToBacenta`).\n\nDirect answers to your three questions first, then the graded report.\n\n**1. Does `displayError(..., updateResult.errors[0])` risk leaking sensitive server detail?**\nNo — but only because of a latent type-mismatch bug, not because of good design. `updateResult.errors` on a `useMutation` result is typed `ReadonlyArray<GraphQLFormattedError>` (a plain deserialized `{message, locations, path, extensions}` object), not an `ApolloError` and not an `Error` instance. `getGraphQLErrorMessage()` in `errorHandler.ts` only special-cases `error instanceof ApolloError` and `error instanceof Error`; a plain object falls through to `String(error)` → `\"[object Object]\"`. So today, no message text renders at all for the non-collision branch — it's a UX bug (uninformative toast), not a leak. See Medium/Low findings below for the latent risk if that helper is later \"fixed\" to read `.message` directly.\n\n**2. Is the collision payload (memberId, firstName, lastName, bacentaName of the other member) pre-existing or new?**\nPre-existing, confirmed by `git status` (only `UpdateMember.tsx` is modified; `UpdateMember.test.tsx` is new — `MemberCollisionDialog.tsx`, `errorHandler.ts`, and the backend `memberContactCollisionError`/`UpdateMemberDetails` are untouched). The pre-fix `catch` block already did `error?.graphQLErrors?.find(err => err?.extensions?.collision)` → `setCollision(...)` and rendered the same dialog. SYN-205 only duplicates that same extraction for the `updateResult.errors` code path so the (already-designed) dialog actually fires under `errorPolicy: 'all'`. No new data is exposed by this change.\n\n**3. Does the fix bypass or weaken `isAuth`/permission checks in this file?**\nNo. The diff is frontend-only, additive logic inside `onSubmit`; it doesn't touch `ProtectedRoute`, any resolver, or `context.jwt.roles` handling. If anything it's a net integrity improvement: previously, a failed `UpdateMemberDetails` (e.g. blocked by a collision) still fell through and ran `UpdateMemberBacenta`/`UpdateMemberBasonta` and navigated away — i.e. a partial write where the bacenta/basonta relationship changed even though the actual profile write was rejected (violates ADR-005, server as source of truth). The fix's early `return` on `updateResult.errors?.length` now correctly prevents those follow-up mutations from running against a failed base update.\n\n## Medium\n\n- `web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/UpdateMember.tsx:149` / `web-react-ts/src/utils/errorHandler.ts:8-37` — `displayError(title, updateResult.errors[0])` passes a plain `GraphQLFormattedError` object that `getGraphQLErrorMessage` doesn't recognize (only `ApolloError`/`Error` are handled), so it silently degrades to `String(error)`.\n  Impact: currently benign (message doesn't leak, but also doesn't display — a UX regression for genuine non-collision errors). Latent risk: `api/src/resolvers/directory/directory-resolvers.ts:180-198` (`UpdateMemberDetails`'s `session.executeWrite(...)`) has no `catch`/`throwToSentry` wrapping — an unexpected Neo4j error (e.g. a race-condition constraint violation) would propagate to the client as a raw driver message. If `getGraphQLErrorMessage` is later fixed to read `.message` off a formatted error (a natural fix for the bug above), that raw message would render verbatim in a user-facing toast.\n  Fix: add a `GraphQLFormattedError`-aware branch to `getGraphQLErrorMessage` (check for a `message` string property before falling back to `String()`), and wrap `UpdateMemberDetails`'s write in `try/catch` → `throwToSentry('There was an error updating the member profile', error)` to guarantee only a sanitized message ever reaches `extensions`/`message`, matching the pattern already used in `ReactivateMemberToBacenta`.\n\n## Low\n\n- `web-react-ts/src/pages/directory/update/UpdateMember.tsx:149-152` — non-collision GraphQL errors currently render as `\"[object Object]\"` in the toast (see Medium finding above for the root cause). Not a security leak, but worth a quick follow-up since it defeats the purpose of surfacing the error to the user at all.\n  Fix: same as the Medium fix above.\n\n- `api/src/resolvers/directory/directory-resolvers.ts:137-179` (pre-existing, **not introduced by this diff**) — `UpdateMemberDetails`'s uniqueness pre-check (`checkMemberContactExistsOnOther`) runs org-wide with no scope restriction, so any `permitLeaderAdmin('Bacenta')` user can learn another member's first/last name, bacenta name, and active/inactive status anywhere in the org simply by submitting a matching email/WhatsApp number. This is an intentional feature of the collision-resolution UX (same payload shape as `MemberCollisionDialog` expects) rather than a bug introduced here, but it is a standing minor cross-scope information disclosure worth a conscious sign-off from the team if not already accepted.\n\n## Note (adjacent code, pre-existing, out of scope for this diff but worth flagging)\n\n- `api/src/resolvers/directory/directory-resolvers.ts:137-138` — `UpdateMemberDetails` checks `isAuth(permitLeaderAdmin('Bacenta'), ...)` but, unlike its siblings in the same file (`CreateMember` → `assertChurchScope`, `UpdateMemberBacenta` → `assertScopeViaMember` + `assertChurchScope`, `ReactivateMemberToBacenta` → `assertChurchScope`, each with SYN-186/SYN-185 IDOR-fix comments), it never validates that `args.id` (the member being edited) belongs to the caller's own scope.\n  Impact: a Bacenta-level leader/admin can call `UpdateMemberDetails` with an arbitrary member ID from anywhere in the organization and overwrite that member's name, email, phone, WhatsApp number, gender, DOB, marital status, and occupation — a real IDOR, same class as the ones already patched in this file.\n  Fix: add `await assertScopeViaMember(context, args.id)` as the second line, matching the pattern already established for `UpdateMemberBacenta`/`ReactivateMemberToBacenta`. This is unrelated to SYN-205 and should be tracked as its own ticket rather than folded into this PR.\n\nNo Critical or High findings originate from the SYN-205 diff itself. The diff is auth-neutral, does not touch Cypher, does not introduce a new data exposure, and closes a real data-integrity bug (partial writes on rejected updates).","usage":{"total_tokens":51688,"tool_uses":20,"duration_ms":199730},"uuid":"fcdcefe1-c854-43ad-becf-d0ed21e134af","session_id":"1f8dd599-a4b3-4691-9eeb-51a7fceb4862"}
